<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7652&amp;p=78237#p78237"><![CDATA[
Well it took, 2 friggin' weeks.....<br /><br /> <img src="http://forums.nesdev.com/images/smilies/icon_evil.gif" alt=":evil:" title="Evil or Very Mad" /> <br /><br />But I THINK I have an at least mostly fully functioning NES Square Wave going.<br /><br />Only problem is that some of the wavelength values I give produce a sound that's kind of off. That probably has to do with me using whole numbers, maybe, but it's not that big a deal. At least most of the them sound accurate. It's apparently just the high frequency ones that sound off. Like wavelength 8 sounds accurate, but 9 and A sounds off, but B sounds accurate. They don't sound too off though.<br /><br />However, even though I've mostly gotten the square channel working, I had to go through quite the headache to get it going and I had to do some things that I'm pretty sure the wiki or the apu_ref doesn't clearly tell you(as far as I've noticed).<br /><br />I have to give a big thanks to miker00lz for which I probably never would of figured out that I have to use a 16 step sequence for the duty cycle. But....why? In the wiki it says it's 8-step, but when I try 8-step the sound is quite off. When I do the 16-step that miker does, it's accurate.<br /><br />Secondly, the negate bit on the sweep register. The wiki and apu_ref says that it inverts the bits.... now, when it says 'invert the bits' I'm thinking that it means <strong>shifter xor 0xFFFF</strong>. How ever every time I try that it gives a sound that sound nothing like a sweep or I get an overflow exception from Visual Basic .NET(is it supposed to wrap around?). But when I looked at miker's code and saw that he just simply subtracted the shifter value(and I saw this in the NESSOUND document), I tried that and it worked! Just what does the wiki mean by 'invert the bits?'<br /><br />Wait...ok it seems that the 'invert the bits' idea isn't there anymore &gt;_&gt; But the one I download to take home had the line:<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />If the negate flag is set, the shifted value's bits are inverted<br /></div><br /><br />Mind you I don't have the internet at home so I can't keep checking the wiki unfortunetly...<br /><br /><br />Another problem that has nothing to do with the simulation or emulation, is<br />the looping. It might just be XNA(mind you I'm using XNA with Visual Basic, which is not 'supported'), but I just cannot get the buffer to loop without some popping sound in between. Unfortunetly I still don't quite understand how streaming works. <br /><br />One last thing, that isn't really a 'problem' cause it works, but I feel I'm doing it wrong. When's the proper time to reset the timer's period after a sweep? I just do it after the buffer's done getting filled and it works fine for my sound simulation, but it may or may not fly in emulation. Maybe I just missed it in the wiki.<br /><br />Ok, thanks everyone for helping! I'd love to think it'll be smooth sailing for implementing the triangle and noise channels, but I've learned in my experience not to hold my breath...<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4007">Undubbed</a> — Mon May 16, 2011 10:13 am</p><hr />
