<title type="html"><![CDATA[I give up, I can't find a way to emulate chiptune sound!]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7652&amp;p=77763#p77763"><![CDATA[
Oh thanks, for the help! I actually given up hope on this topic after I didn't get more replies after the first for a long time, and I hunkered down to try to understand sound myself. Took a darn long time, but I think my understanding of constructing my own sound buffers have gotten WAY better.<br /><br />I have, in fact, got a working square wave and triangle wave generator, but I've yet to actually put in things like envelope decay, duty cycle, counters, and sweep which is what I'm working on now.<br /><br />Right now, I'm making a program in Visual Basic .NET(Easier to make a user interface)  that plays all the sound the same way the nes does. A sound test of sorts.  Using XNA for sound.<br /><br />Before that, I made a program on the NES that does the exact same thing, just on the NES, of course. Made it so that I have a quick way to gauge which values in which registers make what sound AND so that I get familiar with NES programming. I might come back with the file if anyone really wants it, the only problem is that you can't quickly go through the wavelength variable and I don't feel like fixing it <img src="http://forums.nesdev.com/images/smilies/icon_sad.gif" alt=":(" title="Sad" /><br /><br />I'm also making a Wave Analyzer in Visual Basic that shows how a wave looks. It's supposed to help me have a better understanding of sine waves, since I had trouble understanding.<br /><br />I'm sure I have a good understanding of duty cycle, but I'm not sure what's the best way to do envelope decay. All I really know is that every 240 / (decay_variable + 1) cycles I'm supposed to down some volume counter. <br /><br />My idea is this:<br /><br />1. Find out the samples per cycle<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">Samples_Per_Cycle = Sample_Rate / Samples<br />ex: 44100 / 735 = 60 samples per cycle</div><br /><br />2. Find out the sample period<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">Sample_Period = Sample_Rate / Wave_Frequency</div><br /><br />3. Multiply Samples_Per_Cycle by the Sample_Period to get how many samples go by before I down the counter. We'll call it Samples_Per_Envelope_Decrement<br /><br />4. Make an array that holds the decrements and declare the counter<br />In Visual Basic .NET<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">// &amp;HF = 0x0F<br />Dim envelope_decay_counter As Integer = &amp;HF<br />Dim envelope_decay&#40;&amp;HF&#41; As Single<br />For i = 0 to UBound&#40;envelop_decay&#41;<br /><br />    // Lower amplitude by 6.25%<br />    envelope_decay&#40;i&#41; = i * 0.0625<br />Next i<br /> </div><br /><br />4. In the loop that loads the sound buffer, every Samples_Per_Envelope_Decrement the envelope_decay_counter goes down by one<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">Dim amp As Single = 1.0<br />For sample_index = 0 to Samples<br />// Buncha code for preparing buffer and calculation<br />buffer&#40;sample_index&#41; = amp - envelope_decay&#40;envelope_decay_counter&#41;<br />If sample_index &gt;= Samples_Per_Envelope_Decrement<br />     envelope_decay_counter -= 1<br />End If<br /><br /><br />Next sample_index<br /></div><br /><br />Haven't actually done any of this yet, but that's my basic plan. I know I left out a ton of stuff in the code and some glaring flaws like what to do when envelope_decay_counter reaches zero, the negative portion of the period(-amp) but it's just a basic mock up of what I want to do. The idea is more than likely bad, but I have nothing else to go on <img src="http://forums.nesdev.com/images/smilies/icon_sad.gif" alt=":(" title="Sad" /><br /><br />I'll show my actual code later today or on monday, maybe.<br /><br />In the meantime I'll check out miker00lz's code and try to implement envelope and duty cycle in my sound test program today.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4007">Undubbed</a> — Fri May 06, 2011 12:06 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
